The paper deals with the problem of efficient communication between a client and a data-centre for updating a file that has undergone insertion-deletion (InDel) processes. This involves compression algorithms that use dynamic programming and entropy coding. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.IT (Information Theory), which deals with the efficient encoding, transmission, and storage of information. 

The paper also involves the study of two models for the source files/edit patterns: the random pre-edit sequence left-to-right random InDel (RPES-LtRRID) process, and the arbitrary pre-edit sequence arbitrary InDel (APES-AID) process. This suggests that the paper may also belong to the sub-categories cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing), which deal with the efficient processing and management of data. 

Furthermore, the paper involves the study of throughput- and computationally-efficient communication, which suggests that it may also belong to the sub-categories cs.CC (Computational Complexity) and cs.SI (Social and Information Networks), which deal with the analysis and design of efficient algorithms and systems for communication and networking.
